<h2>Local Keyword Research for Auto Repair Shops</h2>
<p>Keywords are the bridge between what customers search and what your website says. Without the right keywords, Google cannot match your shop to the right searches.</p>
<p>Auto repair <a href="/blog/local-keyword-research/">keyword research</a> follows a specific pattern. Most high-value searches combine a service with a location modifier.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="High-value keywords for auto repair shops" src="/images/blog/auto-repair-seo-keywords.webp" /></p>
<h3>Three Types of Keywords to Target</h3>
<p><strong>Service + Location Keywords</strong>. These drive the most calls. "Brake repair Dallas," "oil change Austin," and "mechanic Houston" are examples. Every city and service combination is a separate keyword to target.</p>
<p><strong>"Near Me" Keywords</strong>. Google handles these based on the searcher's GPS location. "Auto repair near me" gets 165,000 monthly searches nationally. You rank for these by having strong local signals, not by stuffing "near me" into your pages.</p>
<p><strong>Informational Keywords</strong>. Questions like "how much does a timing belt replacement cost" or "what does a check engine light mean" bring in customers earlier in their journey. These work best as blog posts.</p>
<h3>How to Find Your Keywords</h3>
<p>Follow this process:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] List every service your shop offers (oil changes, brakes, transmission, diagnostics, tires, AC, engine repair)</li>
<li>[ ] Add your city and nearby city names to each service</li>
<li>[ ] Check Google autocomplete by typing each service and noting suggestions</li>
<li>[ ] Review the "People Also Ask" section for question-based keywords</li>
<li>[ ] Look at competitor websites to see which services they highlight</li>
</ul>
<p>Use free tools to validate search volume. Our guide to the <a href="/best/best-free-keyword-research-tools/">best free keyword research tools</a> lists options that do not require paid subscriptions.</p>
<h3>Map Keywords to Pages</h3>
<p>Every service keyword needs its own page. Do not put all services on a single page.</p>
